\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces Distribution of $\log _{10}(n_{\mathrm  {H_2}})$ across six UV field strengths. The seventh cube, $G_0= 0.2$, closely resembles $G_0= 0.1$ and is omitted from this figure only to avoid visual redundancy; it is included in all quantitative analyses. The bimodal structure at low $G_0$ (UV-exposed and self-shielded populations) collapses to a single UV-dominated mode as $G_0$ increases. Dashed lines mark per-cube means. All modelling is performed in log-space.}}{4}{figure.1}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:histograms}{{1}{4}{Distribution of $\logn $ across six UV field strengths. The seventh cube, $\Gzero = 0.2$, closely resembles $\Gzero = 0.1$ and is omitted from this figure only to avoid visual redundancy; it is included in all quantitative analyses. The bimodal structure at low $\Gzero $ (UV-exposed and self-shielded populations) collapses to a single UV-dominated mode as $\Gzero $ increases. Dashed lines mark per-cube means. All modelling is performed in log-space}{figure.1}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {2}{\ignorespaces Schematic comparison of per-cell modelling (\emph  {left}) and the multi-scale spatial neighbourhood representation used here (\emph  {right}). Note that the 15-feature baseline already includes one non-local quantity, the solver-computed self-shielding factor $f_{\mathrm  {H_2}}$; what the spatial features add is explicit neighbourhood context for \emph  {all} fields, including the directly observable ones, at three nested scales.}}{4}{figure.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:diagram}{{2}{4}{Schematic comparison of per-cell modelling (\emph {left}) and the multi-scale spatial neighbourhood representation used here (\emph {right}). Note that the 15-feature baseline already includes one non-local quantity, the solver-computed self-shielding factor $\fshield $; what the spatial features add is explicit neighbourhood context for \emph {all} fields, including the directly observable ones, at three nested scales}{figure.2}{}}
